                      <p><strong><em>                      <strong><em>                      <strong><em> The year of the Tiger: </em></strong></em></strong></em></strong><em><em><em> In our May, 2004 issue (<a href="http://www.consortiuminfo.org/bulletins/may04.php">Standards as Trade Barriers</a> ) we focused on the use of standards by governments to protect domestic industry, using a current standoff between the United States semiconductor industry and China, which had adopted a &ldquo;home grown&rdquo; standard in preference to the globally implemented WiFi standard (see: <a href="http://www.consortiuminfo.org/bulletins/may04.php#trends">Breaking Down Trade Barriers: Avoiding the China Syndrome</a> ) But with or without trade barriers, China is flexing its muscles, as the selection of articles below indicate, from the first &ndash; which shows that the standards world is now willing to go to Beijing, rather than expect Beijing to go to it &ndash; to the second, illustrating the power of China&rsquo;s centrally managed economy to control access to its enormous consumer population -- to the last two, which illustrate that there are still issues to resolve between China and the rest of the global standards community.</em></em></em> </p>
